guably have always tried to get outside or beyond themselves and society. The drive to exceed some limit or condition of finitude is an eduring aspect of culture, even in a "disenchanted" society that may have cut off most paths of access to the Beyond. The contributors to this volume demonstrate the humanity of Transcendence in various ways: as an effort to get beyond our crass physical materiality; as spiritual entrepreneurship; as the ecstasy of rituals of possession; and as a literary, aesthetic, and semiotic event. These efforts build from a shared conviction that Transcendene is thoroughly human, and accordingly avoid purely confessional and parochial approches while taking seriously the various claims and behavioral expressions of traditions in which Transcendence has been understood in theological terms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aTranscendence of God. 4aAchsenzeit. 4aImmanenz. 4aSemiotik. 4aTranszendenz. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aAxial Age.  aTranscendence.  aimmanence.  asemiotics.1 aAbrutyn, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenavides, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrech, Volkhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehnert, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeone, Massimo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPonzo, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPonzo, Jenny, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVolli, Ugo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilkens, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYelle, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https:/